[49m[38;5;9m- 817     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Fairness monitoring.** Duplicate detection doesn't have the same fairness concerns as a clinical risk model, but it's not fairness-free either. If your scorer systematically flags claims from certain provider categories (small practices, rural providers, non-English-documentation claims) at higher rates than the underlying duplicate base rate in that subgroup, you have a problem. Add subgroup monitoring on the auto-suspend rate by provider size, geography, and specialty. Disparities that can't be explained by the underlying duplicate rate are a signal to investigate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      817[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Fairness monitoring.** Duplicate detection doesn't have the same fairness concerns as a clinical risk model, but it's not fairness-free either. If your scorer systematically flags claims from certain provider categories (small practices, rural providers, non-English-documentation claims) at higher rates than the underlying duplicate base rate in that subgroup, you have a problem. Add subgroup monitoring on the auto-suspend rate by provider size, geography, and specialty. Disparities that can't be explained by the underlying duplicate rate are a signal to investigate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      818[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      819[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trigger idempotency.** S3 ObjectCreated events and asynchronous Lambda invocations are at-least-once delivery. A redelivered event re-runs the parser, which re-triggers the detector, which (without guards) writes a duplicate suspension record and a duplicate SQS review-queue message. The pseudocode above uses conditional DynamoDB writes (`attribute_not_exists`) at both the parser side (claim-history PutItem) and the detector side (claim-decisions PutItem keyed on a deterministic hash of the claim pair and model version) to make each invocation idempotent. This pattern recurs across any event-driven Lambda pipeline; if you're building multiple recipes from this chapter, consider extracting idempotency into a shared utility layer or a chapter-wide appendix.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      820[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      821[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dead-letter queues on every async Lambda.** Lambda's default async retry behavior (two retries over six hours, then silently drop) means a malformed 837 that crashes the parser disappears from operational state. The raw file stays in S3 but the fact that it failed to process is captured only in CloudWatch Logs, where nobody is looking. Configure an `OnFailure` async destination (an SQS dead-letter queue) on the parser, detector, and label-writer Lambdas. Alarm on DLQ depth. Reprocess from the DLQ after fixing the root cause.
