Purpose: S1: expand PHI paragraph in Why This Isn't Production-Ready to address free-text minimization

[49m[38;5;9m- 815     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **PHI in the review queue and labels.** SQS messages and label records contain enough PHI to require careful controls. Encrypt at rest with customer-managed KMS keys. Keep retention short on SQS (the queue is a work-in-progress store, not an archive). The label store is the long-lived one; scope read access tightly (the label-writer Lambda, the retraining job, named audit roles).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      815[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **PHI in the review queue and labels.** SQS messages and label records contain enough PHI to require careful controls. Encrypt at rest with customer-managed KMS keys. Keep retention short on SQS (the queue is a work-in-progress store, not an archive). The label store is the long-lived one; scope read access tightly (the label-writer Lambda, the retraining job, named audit roles). Examiner free-text reasoning is especially problematic: examiners working with the patient record open in another tab routinely paste identifiers, clinical context, and names into their notes. The pipeline scrubs this text before write (see `scrub_phi_from_text` in Step 5), but the minimum-necessary principle applies here with force: rely on the controlled-vocabulary `reasoning_code` for operational and training signal, retain scrubbed text only for edge-case audits, and review the scrubber's effectiveness quarterly.
