[49m[38;5;9m- 854     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Real-time at the 837 ingestion edge.** Swap the S3-event trigger for an API endpoint or a Kinesis stream sitting between the clearinghouse connection and the adjudication queue. Detection happens in the same submission-to-adjudication window rather than after the claim lands in the queue. Benefits: faster feedback to providers (duplicate denial within minutes rather than hours). Costs: tighter integration with the upstream pipeline, and the detector's latency budget shrinks significantly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      854[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time at the 837 ingestion edge.** Swap the S3-event trigger for an API endpoint or a Kinesis stream sitting between the clearinghouse connection and the adjudication queue. Detection happens in the same submission-to-adjudication window rather than after the claim lands in the queue. Benefits: faster feedback to providers (duplicate denial within minutes rather than hours). Costs: tighter integration with the upstream pipeline, and the detector's latency budget shrinks significantly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      855[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      856[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **OpenSearch for high-volume fuzzy name matching.** The core walkthrough performs Levenshtein and Jaccard similarity inline in Lambda, which works well when the blocking-key fields are system-generated identifiers (patient IDs, NPIs, claim numbers). Once you add patient-name or provider-name fields to the scoring layer, the fuzzy-match volume grows and an inline implementation starts hitting Lambda's memory and latency budgets. Promote OpenSearch into the pipeline at that point: index claim records with a phonetic analyzer (Double Metaphone or Beider-Morse) on name fields, and issue edit-distance queries from the detector Lambda as a Step 2.5 between blocking and scoring. OpenSearch also supports k-NN vector search if you later add embedding-based similarity (see below). The cost tradeoff: OpenSearch is a fixed monthly cost ($75-200+ for a small domain) regardless of claim volume, versus the per-invocation cost of inline matching. The crossover point where OpenSearch becomes cheaper depends on your claim volume and the number of name fields you score.
